{"title_page": "LGBT History Month", "text_new": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name  = LGBT History Month\n|type          = National\n|image         = \n|imagesize     =\n|caption       = \n|official_name =\n|nickname      = \n|observedby    = Australia<br/>Canada<br/>Hungary<br/>United Kingdom<br/>United States<br/>Ireland \n|litcolor      =\n|longtype      = National, civil rights, cultural, ethnic, sexual orientation, HRC, gay, lesbian, bisexual, transgender \n|significance  = Celebration of [[LGBT history]]\n|begins        = February <small>(United Kingdom)</small><br/>May <small>(Ireland)</small><br/>October <small>(United States)</small><br/>October <small> (Canada)</small><br/>\n|ends          = \n|date          = 1994\n|celebrations  = \n|observances   =\n|relatedto     =\n|scheduling    = varies\n|duration      = 1 month\n|frequency     = Annual\n}}\n'''LGBT History Month''' is an annual month-long observance of lesbian, gay, [[bisexual]] and [[transgender]] history, and the history of the [[List of LGBT rights by region|gay rights]] and related [[civil rights]] movements.<ref name=\"glsen\">[http://www.glsen.org/cgi-bin/iowa/educator/library/record/816.html LGBT History Month Resources] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618034421/http://www.glsen.org/cgi-bin/iowa/educator/library/record/816.html |date=18 June 2013 }}</ref> LGBT History Month provides role models, builds community, and represents a civil rights statement about the contributions of the LGBT community.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=NEA drops plan for gay history month|last=K.L. Billingsley|date=21 July 1996|work=The Washington Times}}</ref> As of 2020, LGBT History Month is a month-long celebration that is specific to Hungary, the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, Brazil, Greenland, and the city of Berlin. \n\nIn the United States, Canada, and Australia, it is celebrated in October to coincide with National Coming Out Day on 11 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/09/02/op-ed-story-behind-first-lgbt-history-month|title=Op-ed: The Story Behind the First LGBT History Month|date=2 September 2015|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> In Hungary and the United Kingdom, it is observed during February; in the UK this coincides with a major celebration of the 2003 abolition of [[Section 28]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://lgbthistorymonth.org.uk/|title=Home|newspaper=Lesbian Gay Bisexual Trans History Month|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> In Berlin, It is known as Queer History Month and is celebrated in June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fu-berlin.de/campusleben/lernen-und-lehren/2014/140203_queer-history-month/index.html|title=Erster Berliner Queer History Month|date=3 February 2014|website=fu-berlin.de|language=de|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== National celebrations ==\n\n=== Australia ===\nIn October 2016, Minus 18 organised the first Australian LGBT History Month in partnership with the [[Australian Lesbian and Gay Archives]], and the Safe Schools Coalition Victoria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minus18.org.au/index.php/get-involved/campaigns/history-month|title=LGBTI History Month|website=minus18.org.au|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/national-news/victoria-news/lgbti-history-month/152671|title=Schools in Victoria to celebrate first LGBTI History Month|last=Wadw|first=Matthew|last2=|first2=|date=8 September 2016|website=Star Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Brazil ===\nBrazil celebrates LGBT History Month.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/02/22/lgbt-history-month-whither-nigeria/|title=LGBT History Month: Whither Nigeria|last=Okeugo|first=Peter|date=2018-02-22|website=Washington Blade: Gay News, Politics, LGBT Rights|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Canada ===\nCanada celebrates LGBT History Month in October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/celebrate-lgbt-history-month|title=Celebrate LGBT History Month|date=2011-10-03|website=GLAAD|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Greenland ===\nGreenland celebrates LGBT History Month.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Hungary ===\nLGBT History Month has been celebrated in February since 2013, and the planned 2020 event is the 8th.<ref name=\":4\" /> The program series is coordinated by [[H\u00e1tt\u00e9r Society]] and [[Labrisz Lesbian Association]], events are organized in partnership with other LGBT organization, cultural and academic institutions, professional organizations etc. The majority of the events take place in [[Budapest]], but a few events are also organized in larger cities all over the country, e.g. in [[Debrecen]], [[P\u00e9cs]], [[Miskolc]] and [[Szeged]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lmbttortenetihonap.hu|title=LMBT T\u00f6rt\u00e9neti h\u00f3nap|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 there were nearly 30 events in the cities of [[Budapest]], [[Miskolc]] and [[Szeged]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://lmbttortenetihonap.hu/bemutatkozas|title=Bemutatkoz\u00e1s|date=2014-01-05|website=LMBT T\u00f6rt\u00e9neti H\u00f3nap|language=hu|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> In 2015 there were 37 events, with some held in [[Tahit\u00f3tfalu]] and [[Csob\u00e1nka]]<ref name=\":5\" /> As of 2019 there were about 40 events for the celebration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/europe/hungary/articles/lgbtq-culture-in-budapest/|title=Explore Budapest\u2019s Vibrant LGBTQ Culture With a Local Activist|last=Krasznahorkai|first=Emma|website=Culture Trip|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n{{LGBT UK sidebar|pride events}}\nLGBT History Month was initiated in the UK by [[Sue Sanders]] and [[Paul Patrick]] as a Schools OUT UK project, which first took place in February 2005.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/lgbt-history-month-uk-when-february-lesbian-gay-bisexual-transgender-queer-community-celebration-a8755966.html|title=Everything you need to know about LGBT History Month|date=31 January 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> The Month is an annual event in the United Kingdom taking place every February.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe event came in the wake of the abolition of [[Section 28]] in 2003, the [[Employment Equality (Sexual Orientation) Regulations 2003]]<ref name=\":3\" /> as well as the government's proposals to bring in a single equality act and a public duty, although this, in fact, did not come to fruition until 2010.\n\nThe Month is intended as a means to raise awareness of, and combat prejudice against the [[LGBT community]] while celebrating its achievement and diversity and making it more visible.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe first celebration in 2005 saw the organisation of over 150 events around the UK. The second logo for the organisation behind the month was designed by LGBT [[typographer]] Tony Malone in 2006, and was reworked by him in 2007 when it then became the corporate logo for the national committee.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nFrom that point in time, each yearly iteration of the Month started to receive its own mark designed by students of the University of the Arts and later by design students at the [[University of Bedfordshire]].{{Cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n==== England ====\nThe initiative received government backing from the deputy [[DfES]] and Equalities Minister [[Jacqui Smith]], although some sections of the press argued against its [[political correctness]], and pointed out that the sexuality of some historical figures is more a matter of speculation than fact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geocities.ws/cheltmunch/lgbt/main/labels.htm|title=LGBT sub menu|website=geocities.ws|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> Supporters of the event countered that it is important to challenge [[heterosexist]] attitudes in society.\n\nThe [[DfES]] promised funding for LGBT History Month for the first two years to help get the event off the ground. It is now very well established and has garnered support from other sources. Long standing sponsors include the [[Metropolitan Police Service]], the [[Metropolitan Police Authority]], [[Amnesty International]] and the [[Crown Prosecution Service]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe early patrons of the Month included [[Cyril Nri]], [[Ian McKellen]], [[Angela Eagle]], [[Gareth Thomas (rugby)|Gareth Thomas]] and [[Labi Siffre]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nEach year, a \"launch event\" takes place in November, for the following Month. Those events took place in the following locations:{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n* 2005: [[Tate Modern]] (sponsored by [[Southwark Council]])\n* 2006: the Metropolitan Police's [[Empress State Building]]\n* 2007: the [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] offered [[Congress House]]\n* 2008: the main hall of the [[Royal Courts of Justice]]. \n* 2009: [[The Urswick School]]\n* 2010: the [[British Museum]] \n* 2011: the [[Oval cricket ground]] \n* 2012: [[Twickenham Stadium]]. \n* 2013: [[Bletchley Park]] \n* 2014: [[Birmingham University]] \n* 2015: the [[Museum of the Order of St John]]\n* 2016: [[Queens College, Cambridge]]\n* 2017: the [[Museum of Liverpool]]\n*2019: [[British Library|The British Library]]\n\nThrough the years many speakers have spoken at the events. These include [[Ian McKellen]], [[Stella Duffy]], [[Allan Horsfall]], [[Linda Bellos]], [[Baroness Scotland]] and [[Barbara Follett (politician)|Barbara Follett]], [[Michael Cashman]], [[Stuart Milk]], Phyl gyimah opuku and [[Rikki Beadle Blair]] among others.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn 5 March 2009, Prime Minister Gordon Brown hosted a reception at Downing Street to mark the Month.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{citation |title=Gordon Brown hosts first LGBT reception |periodical=PinkNews |date=6 March 2009 |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-11500.html |accessdate=16 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016161913/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-11500.html/ |archive-date=16 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=====OUTing the Past festival and the annual Alan Horsfall Lecture=====\nOUTing The Past is an annual festival of LGBT history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgallery.ie/what-we-do/education-department/special-projects-education-and-learning/outing-past-festival-lgbt|title=OUTing the Past: The Festival of LGBT History|website=National Gallery of Ireland|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> \n\nIn 2015 saw the first edition of ''OUTing The Past'', a festival of LGBT History spearheaded by Dr Jeff Evans. The festival started in three venues in [[Manchester]]: the [[LGBT Foundation (UK)|LGBT Foundation]], The Central Library and the [[People's History Museum|Peoples History Museum.]] Comprising several presentations of diverse history presented by a mixture of academics, LGBT enthusiasts and activists. Sitting alongside the popular presentations was an academic conference with the inaugural [[Allan Horsfall]] Lecture given by Professor Charles Upchurch of Florida University. This is now a yearly event funded by the [[Campaign for Homosexual Equality]]. Stephen M Hornby was appointed as the first National Playwright in Residence to LGBT History Month.  The first production created as a result of this was a three part heritage premiere co-written with Ric Brady and performed across the weekend called \"A Very Victorian Scandal\" which dramatised new research about a drag ball in 1880 in Hulme.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe following year the festival expanded to six hubs around England and the conference had its own slot. The Alan Horsfall lecture was given by Professor [[Susan Stryker]] of the University of Arizona in 2016.  The national heritage premieres were \"Mister Stokes: The Man-Woman of Manchester\" written by Abi Hynes, which told the story of Harry Stokes a Victorian trans pioneer and \"Devils in Human Shape\" by Tom Marshman, which dramatized Georgian sodomy trials in Bristol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northernsoul.me.uk/lgbt-history-stokes/|title=Man-Woman of Manchester: an extraordinary story|date=4 March 2016|website=Northern Soul|access-date=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, there were 18 venues round the country and by now over a hundred presentations on [[LGBT history]] had been given. The Alan Horsfall lecture was given by [[Diana Souhami]].  The national heritage premieres were \"The Burnley Buggers' Ball\" by Stephen M Hornby, which told the story of the first public meeting to establish an LGBT Center in the UK in 1971 at Burnley Library, and \"Burnley's Lesbian Liberator\" by Abi Hynes which told the story of one of the first demonstrations in support of a woman sacked for wearing a Lesbian Liberation badge by the Burnley & Pendle Bus Company in 1978.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/feb/07/burnley-buggers-ball-to-mark-50th-anniversary-of-sexual-offences-act|title=Burnley Buggers' Ball to mark 50th anniversary of Sexual Offences Act|last=correspondent|first=Mark Brown Arts|date=7 February 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 September 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, there were 11 venues which included [[Wales]] and [[Northern Ireland]]. The lecture was given by [[Tom Robinson]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n2019 there were 18 venues including the first international events in The [[Republic of Ireland]], Sweden, [[Norway]] and New York. The lecture was given by Dr Jeffrey Weeks in Belfast.  The national heritage premiere was \"The Adhesion of Love\" by Stephen M Hornby, which toured to a number of venues in the North West of England.  It told the story of a visit by a member of the [[Eagle Street College]] to [[Walt Whitman]] in 1891.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/17509144.playwright-stephen-m-hornby-highlights-bolton-link-with-the-adhesion-of-love-play-at-museum/|title=REVIEW: The Adhesion of Love at Bolton Museum|website=The Bolton News|access-date=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016, Schools OUT UK has partnered with a several contract publishers to produce magazines as an Official Guide to LGBT History Month, putting 35,000 copies of their publication into every secondary school in the UK, plus community spaces, charities and businesses. The magazine had introductions from the leaders of all the main political parties and the [[Mayor of London]]. The magazine's Diversity Dashboard runs job adverts and events listings from LGBT-friendly employers and the community.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==== Scotland ====\nIn 2005 and 2006, LGBT History Month was celebrated in [[Scotland]] as an LGBT community event, receiving support from LGBT community history projects such as [[Our Story Scotland]] and Remember When.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nls.uk/collections/topics/lgbt-research-resources|title=Guide to LGBT research resources \u2013 National Library of Scotland|website=nls.uk|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor 2007 and 2008, the [[Scottish Government]] provided funding for a post at [[LGBT Youth Scotland]] to bring LGBT History Month into the wider community, including schools and youth groups.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 2020 Scotland's theme was \"What have we learned? 20 years since the repeal of Section 28.\" <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotland.org/features/lgbt-history-month-dedicated-to-celebrating-scotlands-lgbt-culture|title=LGBT History Month {{!}} Scotland.org|website=Scotland|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n{{hatnote|Not to be confused with [[LGBT Pride Month]] celebrated in June.}}\n{{See also|Lesbian American history|Gay men in American history|Bisexual American history|Transgender American history}}\n\nLGBT History Month originated in the United States, and was first celebrated in 1994. It was founded by Missouri high-school history teacher Rodney Wilson. Wilson originated the idea, served as founder on the first coordinating committee, and chose October as the month of celebration.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2018/10/know-history-behind-lgbt-history-month/|title=Do you know the history behind LGBT History Month?|last=Smith|first=Gwendolyn|date=1 October 2018|website=LGBTQ Nation|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"advocate.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/09/02/op-ed-story-behind-first-lgbt-history-month|title=Op-ed: The Story Behind the First LGBT History Month|date=2 September 2015|website=advocate.com|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> Among early supporters and members of the first coordinating committee were [[Kevin Jennings]] of the [[Gay, Lesbian and Straight Education Network]] (GLSEN); Kevin Boyer of the [[Gerber/Hart Gay and Lesbian Library and Archives]] in Chicago; Paul Varnell, writer for the [[Windy City Times]]; Torey Wilson, Chicago area teacher; Johnda Boyce, women's studies major at Columbus State University and Jessea Greenman of UC-Berkeley.<ref name=\"advocate.com\" /> Many gay and lesbian organizations supported the concept early on as did Governors William Weld of Massachusetts and Lowell Weicker of Connecticut, Mayors such as Thomas Menino of Boston and Wellington Webb of Denver, who recognized the inaugural month with official proclamations. In 1995, the [[National Education Association]] indicated support of LGBT History Month as well as other history months by resolution at its General Assembly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/lgbt-pride-month/about/|title=About {{!}} Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Pride Month {{!}} Library of Congress|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOctober was chosen by Wilson as the month for the celebration because [[National Coming Out Day]] on 11 October, chosen to mark the date of the [[Second National March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights|Second March of Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights]] in 1987, was already established as a widely known event.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/02/22/lgbt-history-month-whither-nigeria/|title=LGBT History Month: Whither Nigeria|date=22 February 2018|website=Washington Blade: Gay News, Politics, LGBT Rights|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> October also commemorated the first [[National March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights]] by [[LGBT]] people in 1979.<ref name=\":1\" /> LGBT History Month is intended to encourage honesty and openness about being LGBT.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWhile it was first known as Lesbian and Gay History Month, the coordinating committee soon added \"bisexual\" to the title. It has subsequently become known as LGBT History Month. The event has received criticism from conservative groups, such as the [[Concerned Women for America]] and others who believe it to be a form of \"[[indoctrination]].\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 2 June 2000, President [[Bill Clinton]] declared June \"Gay & Lesbian Pride Month\" to commemorate the June 1969 [[Stonewall riots]] in [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref name=\"whitehouse\">{{citation|title=Clinton Declares June 2000 Gay & Lesbian Pride Month|date=2 June 2000|url=http://usgovinfo.about.com/library/weekly/blgaylesproc.htm|periodical=About.com|accessdate=17 June 2008}}</ref> On 1 June 2009, President Barack Obama expanded the commemoration further by declaring June Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Pride Month.<ref name=\"obama\">{{citation|title=President Hails Gay Pride Month|date=2 June 2009|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2009/06/67521623/1|periodical=USA Today|accessdate=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n \nIn 2011, Equality Forum introduced an internal search engine for all Icons from inception in 2006 to present. By clicking on \"Icon Search\" and choosing one of hundreds of categories<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/equality-forum-website-provides-31-new-icons-for-lgbt-history-month|title=Equality Forum website provides 31 new icons for LGBT History Month \u2013 National Constitution Center|website=National Constitution Center \u2013 constitutioncenter.org|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> such as African-American, athlete, California, Germany, HIV/AIDS, Military, Religion, Transgender, Youth; visitors to the site will be provided with links to all Icons in that category.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nIn 2012, for the first time, two American school districts celebrated LGBT History Month. The [[Broward County Public Schools|Broward County school]] district in Florida signed a resolution in September in support of LGBT Americans, and later that year the Los Angeles school district, America's second-largest, also signed on.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://inamerica.blogs.cnn.com/2012/10/08/two-school-districts-recognize-lgbt-month/?hpt=us_bn1|title=Two school districts recognize LGBT Month|date=8 October 2012|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n== Citywide celebrations ==\n\n=== Berlin ===\nIn [[Berlin]], it is known as Queer History Month instead of LGBT History Month. Every year it takes place in June. It is to educate and help people deal with sexual, [[sexual diversity]], and anti-discrimination in small projects.<ref name=\"queerhistory.de\">{{Cite web|url=http://queerhistory.de/|title=queerhistory.de {{!}} teaching queer history|website=queerhistory.de|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring Queer History Month (QHM), people are able to find detailed lessons on queer history suitable for both school and non-school education. Also, educational institutions provide education to schools and youth institutions directly.<ref name=\"queerhistory.de\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n*[[Bisexual American history]]\n*[[Gay men in American history]]\n*[[History of bisexuality]]\n*[[History of lesbianism]]\n*[[Lesbian American history]]\n*[[LGBT history]]\n*[[:Category:LGBT history]]\n*[[Gay and Lesbian Pride Month]] (June)\n*[[Transgender American history]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://lgbthistorymonth.com/ LGBT History Month website \u2013 US]\n*[http://www.lgbthistorymonth.org.uk/ LGBT History Month website \u2013 UK]\n*[http://www.lgbthistorymonth.co.uk/ Schools OUT UK's Official Guide to LGBT History Month magazine and Diversity Dashboard]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190508094843/http://www.lgbthistorymonthmagazine.co.uk/ LGBT History Month Magazine: The Official Guide to LGBT History Month UK]\n* https://www.minus18.org.au/index.php/get-involved/campaigns/history-month\n{{LGBT history}}\n\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1994]]\n[[Category:LGBT history]]\n[[Category:LGBT events in the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:February observances]]\n[[Category:October observances]]\n[[Category:Commemorative months]]\n[[Category:Observances in the United States]]\n[[Category:Observances in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox holiday\n|holiday_name  = LGBT History Month\n|type          = National\n|image         = \n|imagesize     =\n|caption       = \n|official_name =\n|nickname      = \n|observedby    = Australia<br/>Canada<br/>Hungary<br/>United Kingdom<br/>United States<br/>Ireland \n|litcolor      =\n|longtype      = National, civil rights, cultural, ethnic, sexual orientation, HRC, gay, lesbian, bisexual, transgender \n|significance  = Celebration of [[LGBT history]]\n|begins        = February <small>(United Kingdom)</small><br/>May <small>(Ireland)<small><br/>October <small>(United States)</small><br/>October <small> (Canada)</small><br/>\n|ends          = \n|date          = 1994\n|celebrations  = \n|observances   =\n|relatedto     =\n|scheduling    = varies\n|duration      = 1 month\n|frequency     = Annual\n}}\n'''LGBT History Month''' is an annual month-long observance of lesbian, gay, [[bisexual]] and [[transgender]] history, and the history of the [[List of LGBT rights by region|gay rights]] and related [[civil rights]] movements.<ref name=\"glsen\">[http://www.glsen.org/cgi-bin/iowa/educator/library/record/816.html LGBT History Month Resources] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618034421/http://www.glsen.org/cgi-bin/iowa/educator/library/record/816.html |date=18 June 2013 }}</ref> LGBT History Month provides role models, builds community, and represents a civil rights statement about the contributions of the LGBT community.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|title=NEA drops plan for gay history month|last=K.L. Billingsley|date=21 July 1996|work=The Washington Times}}</ref> As of 2020, LGBT History Month is a month-long celebration that is specific to Hungary, the United States, the United Kingdom, Canada, Australia, Brazil, Greenland, and the city of Berlin. \n\nIn the United States, Canada, and Australia, it is celebrated in October to coincide with National Coming Out Day on 11 October.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/09/02/op-ed-story-behind-first-lgbt-history-month|title=Op-ed: The Story Behind the First LGBT History Month|date=2 September 2015|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> In Hungary and the United Kingdom, it is observed during February; in the UK this coincides with a major celebration of the 2003 abolition of [[Section 28]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://lgbthistorymonth.org.uk/|title=Home|newspaper=Lesbian Gay Bisexual Trans History Month|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> In Berlin, It is known as Queer History Month and is celebrated in June.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fu-berlin.de/campusleben/lernen-und-lehren/2014/140203_queer-history-month/index.html|title=Erster Berliner Queer History Month|date=3 February 2014|website=fu-berlin.de|language=de|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\n== National celebrations ==\n\n=== Australia ===\nIn October 2016, Minus 18 organised the first Australian LGBT History Month in partnership with the [[Australian Lesbian and Gay Archives]], and the Safe Schools Coalition Victoria.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.minus18.org.au/index.php/get-involved/campaigns/history-month|title=LGBTI History Month|website=minus18.org.au|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.starobserver.com.au/news/national-news/victoria-news/lgbti-history-month/152671|title=Schools in Victoria to celebrate first LGBTI History Month|last=Wadw|first=Matthew|last2=|first2=|date=8 September 2016|website=Star Observer|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=4 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Brazil ===\nBrazil celebrates LGBT History Month.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/02/22/lgbt-history-month-whither-nigeria/|title=LGBT History Month: Whither Nigeria|last=Okeugo|first=Peter|date=2018-02-22|website=Washington Blade: Gay News, Politics, LGBT Rights|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Canada ===\nCanada celebrates LGBT History Month in October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.glaad.org/blog/celebrate-lgbt-history-month|title=Celebrate LGBT History Month|date=2011-10-03|website=GLAAD|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Greenland ===\nGreenland celebrates LGBT History Month.<ref name=\":7\" />\n\n=== Hungary ===\nLGBT History Month has been celebrated in February since 2013, and the planned 2020 event is the 8th.<ref name=\":4\" /> The program series is coordinated by [[H\u00e1tt\u00e9r Society]] and [[Labrisz Lesbian Association]], events are organized in partnership with other LGBT organization, cultural and academic institutions, professional organizations etc. The majority of the events take place in [[Budapest]], but a few events are also organized in larger cities all over the country, e.g. in [[Debrecen]], [[P\u00e9cs]], [[Miskolc]] and [[Szeged]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.lmbttortenetihonap.hu|title=LMBT T\u00f6rt\u00e9neti h\u00f3nap|access-date=2 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 there were nearly 30 events in the cities of [[Budapest]], [[Miskolc]] and [[Szeged]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=http://lmbttortenetihonap.hu/bemutatkozas|title=Bemutatkoz\u00e1s|date=2014-01-05|website=LMBT T\u00f6rt\u00e9neti H\u00f3nap|language=hu|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> In 2015 there were 37 events, with some held in [[Tahit\u00f3tfalu]] and [[Csob\u00e1nka]]<ref name=\":5\" /> As of 2019 there were about 40 events for the celebration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theculturetrip.com/europe/hungary/articles/lgbtq-culture-in-budapest/|title=Explore Budapest\u2019s Vibrant LGBTQ Culture With a Local Activist|last=Krasznahorkai|first=Emma|website=Culture Trip|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== United Kingdom ===\n{{LGBT UK sidebar|pride events}}\nLGBT History Month was initiated in the UK by [[Sue Sanders]] and [[Paul Patrick]] as a Schools OUT UK project, which first took place in February 2005.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/lgbt-history-month-uk-when-february-lesbian-gay-bisexual-transgender-queer-community-celebration-a8755966.html|title=Everything you need to know about LGBT History Month|date=31 January 2019|website=The Independent|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> The Month is an annual event in the United Kingdom taking place every February.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThe event came in the wake of the abolition of [[Section 28]] in 2003, the [[Employment Equality (Sexual Orientation) Regulations 2003]]<ref name=\":3\" /> as well as the government's proposals to bring in a single equality act and a public duty, although this, in fact, did not come to fruition until 2010.\n\nThe Month is intended as a means to raise awareness of, and combat prejudice against the [[LGBT community]] while celebrating its achievement and diversity and making it more visible.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe first celebration in 2005 saw the organisation of over 150 events around the UK. The second logo for the organisation behind the month was designed by LGBT [[typographer]] Tony Malone in 2006, and was reworked by him in 2007 when it then became the corporate logo for the national committee.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nFrom that point in time, each yearly iteration of the Month started to receive its own mark designed by students of the University of the Arts and later by design students at the [[University of Bedfordshire]].{{Cn|date=December 2019}}\n\n==== England ====\nThe initiative received government backing from the deputy [[DfES]] and Equalities Minister [[Jacqui Smith]], although some sections of the press argued against its [[political correctness]], and pointed out that the sexuality of some historical figures is more a matter of speculation than fact.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.geocities.ws/cheltmunch/lgbt/main/labels.htm|title=LGBT sub menu|website=geocities.ws|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref> Supporters of the event countered that it is important to challenge [[heterosexist]] attitudes in society.\n\nThe [[DfES]] promised funding for LGBT History Month for the first two years to help get the event off the ground. It is now very well established and has garnered support from other sources. Long standing sponsors include the [[Metropolitan Police Service]], the [[Metropolitan Police Authority]], [[Amnesty International]] and the [[Crown Prosecution Service]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe early patrons of the Month included [[Cyril Nri]], [[Ian McKellen]], [[Angela Eagle]], [[Gareth Thomas (rugby)|Gareth Thomas]] and [[Labi Siffre]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nEach year, a \"launch event\" takes place in November, for the following Month. Those events took place in the following locations:{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n* 2005: [[Tate Modern]] (sponsored by [[Southwark Council]])\n* 2006: the Metropolitan Police's [[Empress State Building]]\n* 2007: the [[Trades Union Congress|TUC]] offered [[Congress House]]\n* 2008: the main hall of the [[Royal Courts of Justice]]. \n* 2009: [[The Urswick School]]\n* 2010: the [[British Museum]] \n* 2011: the [[Oval cricket ground]] \n* 2012: [[Twickenham Stadium]]. \n* 2013: [[Bletchley Park]] \n* 2014: [[Birmingham University]] \n* 2015: the [[Museum of the Order of St John]]\n* 2016: [[Queens College, Cambridge]]\n* 2017: the [[Museum of Liverpool]]\n*2019: [[British Library|The British Library]]\n\nThrough the years many speakers have spoken at the events. These include [[Ian McKellen]], [[Stella Duffy]], [[Allan Horsfall]], [[Linda Bellos]], [[Baroness Scotland]] and [[Barbara Follett (politician)|Barbara Follett]], [[Michael Cashman]], [[Stuart Milk]], Phyl gyimah opuku and [[Rikki Beadle Blair]] among others.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nOn 5 March 2009, Prime Minister Gordon Brown hosted a reception at Downing Street to mark the Month.<ref name=\"Brown\">{{citation |title=Gordon Brown hosts first LGBT reception |periodical=PinkNews |date=6 March 2009 |url=http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-11500.html |accessdate=16 July 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111016161913/http://www.pinknews.co.uk/news/articles/2005-11500.html/ |archive-date=16 October 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n=====OUTing the Past festival and the annual Alan Horsfall Lecture=====\nOUTing The Past is an annual festival of LGBT history.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgallery.ie/what-we-do/education-department/special-projects-education-and-learning/outing-past-festival-lgbt|title=OUTing the Past: The Festival of LGBT History|website=National Gallery of Ireland|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> \n\nIn 2015 saw the first edition of ''OUTing The Past'', a festival of LGBT History spearheaded by Dr Jeff Evans. The festival started in three venues in [[Manchester]]: the [[LGBT Foundation (UK)|LGBT Foundation]], The Central Library and the [[People's History Museum|Peoples History Museum.]] Comprising several presentations of diverse history presented by a mixture of academics, LGBT enthusiasts and activists. Sitting alongside the popular presentations was an academic conference with the inaugural [[Allan Horsfall]] Lecture given by Professor Charles Upchurch of Florida University. This is now a yearly event funded by the [[Campaign for Homosexual Equality]]. Stephen M Hornby was appointed as the first National Playwright in Residence to LGBT History Month.  The first production created as a result of this was a three part heritage premiere co-written with Ric Brady and performed across the weekend called \"A Very Victorian Scandal\" which dramatised new research about a drag ball in 1880 in Hulme.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\nThe following year the festival expanded to six hubs around England and the conference had its own slot. The Alan Horsfall lecture was given by Professor [[Susan Stryker]] of the University of Arizona in 2016.  The national heritage premieres were \"Mister Stokes: The Man-Woman of Manchester\" written by Abi Hynes, which told the story of Harry Stokes a Victorian trans pioneer and \"Devils in Human Shape\" by Tom Marshman, which dramatized Georgian sodomy trials in Bristol.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.northernsoul.me.uk/lgbt-history-stokes/|title=Man-Woman of Manchester: an extraordinary story|date=4 March 2016|website=Northern Soul|access-date=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, there were 18 venues round the country and by now over a hundred presentations on [[LGBT history]] had been given. The Alan Horsfall lecture was given by [[Diana Souhami]].  The national heritage premieres were \"The Burnley Buggers' Ball\" by Stephen M Hornby, which told the story of the first public meeting to establish an LGBT Center in the UK in 1971 at Burnley Library, and \"Burnley's Lesbian Liberator\" by Abi Hynes which told the story of one of the first demonstrations in support of a woman sacked for wearing a Lesbian Liberation badge by the Burnley & Pendle Bus Company in 1978.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2017/feb/07/burnley-buggers-ball-to-mark-50th-anniversary-of-sexual-offences-act|title=Burnley Buggers' Ball to mark 50th anniversary of Sexual Offences Act|last=correspondent|first=Mark Brown Arts|date=7 February 2017|work=The Guardian|access-date=21 September 2019|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, there were 11 venues which included [[Wales]] and [[Northern Ireland]]. The lecture was given by [[Tom Robinson]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n2019 there were 18 venues including the first international events in The [[Republic of Ireland]], Sweden, [[Norway]] and New York. The lecture was given by Dr Jeffrey Weeks in Belfast.  The national heritage premiere was \"The Adhesion of Love\" by Stephen M Hornby, which toured to a number of venues in the North West of England.  It told the story of a visit by a member of the [[Eagle Street College]] to [[Walt Whitman]] in 1891.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/17509144.playwright-stephen-m-hornby-highlights-bolton-link-with-the-adhesion-of-love-play-at-museum/|title=REVIEW: The Adhesion of Love at Bolton Museum|website=The Bolton News|access-date=21 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nFrom 2016, Schools OUT UK has partnered with a several contract publishers to produce magazines as an Official Guide to LGBT History Month, putting 35,000 copies of their publication into every secondary school in the UK, plus community spaces, charities and businesses. The magazine had introductions from the leaders of all the main political parties and the [[Mayor of London]]. The magazine's Diversity Dashboard runs job adverts and events listings from LGBT-friendly employers and the community.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}}\n\n==== Scotland ====\nIn 2005 and 2006, LGBT History Month was celebrated in [[Scotland]] as an LGBT community event, receiving support from LGBT community history projects such as [[Our Story Scotland]] and Remember When.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nls.uk/collections/topics/lgbt-research-resources|title=Guide to LGBT research resources \u2013 National Library of Scotland|website=nls.uk|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nFor 2007 and 2008, the [[Scottish Government]] provided funding for a post at [[LGBT Youth Scotland]] to bring LGBT History Month into the wider community, including schools and youth groups.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nIn 2020 Scotland's theme was \"What have we learned? 20 years since the repeal of Section 28.\" <ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scotland.org/features/lgbt-history-month-dedicated-to-celebrating-scotlands-lgbt-culture|title=LGBT History Month {{!}} Scotland.org|website=Scotland|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\n=== United States ===\n{{hatnote|Not to be confused with [[LGBT Pride Month]] celebrated in June.}}\n{{See also|Lesbian American history|Gay men in American history|Bisexual American history|Transgender American history}}\n\nLGBT History Month originated in the United States, and was first celebrated in 1994. It was founded by Missouri high-school history teacher Rodney Wilson. Wilson originated the idea, served as founder on the first coordinating committee, and chose October as the month of celebration.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.lgbtqnation.com/2018/10/know-history-behind-lgbt-history-month/|title=Do you know the history behind LGBT History Month?|last=Smith|first=Gwendolyn|date=1 October 2018|website=LGBTQ Nation|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"advocate.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.advocate.com/commentary/2015/09/02/op-ed-story-behind-first-lgbt-history-month|title=Op-ed: The Story Behind the First LGBT History Month|date=2 September 2015|website=advocate.com|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> Among early supporters and members of the first coordinating committee were [[Kevin Jennings]] of the [[Gay, Lesbian and Straight Education Network]] (GLSEN); Kevin Boyer of the [[Gerber/Hart Gay and Lesbian Library and Archives]] in Chicago; Paul Varnell, writer for the [[Windy City Times]]; Torey Wilson, Chicago area teacher; Johnda Boyce, women's studies major at Columbus State University and Jessea Greenman of UC-Berkeley.<ref name=\"advocate.com\" /> Many gay and lesbian organizations supported the concept early on as did Governors William Weld of Massachusetts and Lowell Weicker of Connecticut, Mayors such as Thomas Menino of Boston and Wellington Webb of Denver, who recognized the inaugural month with official proclamations. In 1995, the [[National Education Association]] indicated support of LGBT History Month as well as other history months by resolution at its General Assembly.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/lgbt-pride-month/about/|title=About {{!}} Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Pride Month {{!}} Library of Congress|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOctober was chosen by Wilson as the month for the celebration because [[National Coming Out Day]] on 11 October, chosen to mark the date of the [[Second National March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights|Second March of Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights]] in 1987, was already established as a widely known event.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonblade.com/2018/02/22/lgbt-history-month-whither-nigeria/|title=LGBT History Month: Whither Nigeria|date=22 February 2018|website=Washington Blade: Gay News, Politics, LGBT Rights|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> October also commemorated the first [[National March on Washington for Lesbian and Gay Rights]] by [[LGBT]] people in 1979.<ref name=\":1\" /> LGBT History Month is intended to encourage honesty and openness about being LGBT.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nWhile it was first known as Lesbian and Gay History Month, the coordinating committee soon added \"bisexual\" to the title. It has subsequently become known as LGBT History Month. The event has received criticism from conservative groups, such as the [[Concerned Women for America]] and others who believe it to be a form of \"[[indoctrination]].\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 2 June 2000, President [[Bill Clinton]] declared June \"Gay & Lesbian Pride Month\" to commemorate the June 1969 [[Stonewall riots]] in [[Lower Manhattan]].<ref name=\"whitehouse\">{{citation|title=Clinton Declares June 2000 Gay & Lesbian Pride Month|date=2 June 2000|url=http://usgovinfo.about.com/library/weekly/blgaylesproc.htm|periodical=About.com|accessdate=17 June 2008}}</ref> On 1 June 2009, President Barack Obama expanded the commemoration further by declaring June Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual and Transgender Pride Month.<ref name=\"obama\">{{citation|title=President Hails Gay Pride Month|date=2 June 2009|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/theoval/post/2009/06/67521623/1|periodical=USA Today|accessdate=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n \nIn 2011, Equality Forum introduced an internal search engine for all Icons from inception in 2006 to present. By clicking on \"Icon Search\" and choosing one of hundreds of categories<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/equality-forum-website-provides-31-new-icons-for-lgbt-history-month|title=Equality Forum website provides 31 new icons for LGBT History Month \u2013 National Constitution Center|website=National Constitution Center \u2013 constitutioncenter.org|access-date=1 February 2019}}</ref> such as African-American, athlete, California, Germany, HIV/AIDS, Military, Religion, Transgender, Youth; visitors to the site will be provided with links to all Icons in that category.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nIn 2012, for the first time, two American school districts celebrated LGBT History Month. The [[Broward County Public Schools|Broward County school]] district in Florida signed a resolution in September in support of LGBT Americans, and later that year the Los Angeles school district, America's second-largest, also signed on.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://inamerica.blogs.cnn.com/2012/10/08/two-school-districts-recognize-lgbt-month/?hpt=us_bn1|title=Two school districts recognize LGBT Month|date=8 October 2012|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\n== Citywide celebrations ==\n\n=== Berlin ===\nIn [[Berlin]], it is known as Queer History Month instead of LGBT History Month. Every year it takes place in June. It is to educate and help people deal with sexual, [[sexual diversity]], and anti-discrimination in small projects.<ref name=\"queerhistory.de\">{{Cite web|url=http://queerhistory.de/|title=queerhistory.de {{!}} teaching queer history|website=queerhistory.de|access-date=26 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nDuring Queer History Month (QHM), people are able to find detailed lessons on queer history suitable for both school and non-school education. Also, educational institutions provide education to schools and youth institutions directly.<ref name=\"queerhistory.de\" />\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|LGBT}}\n*[[Bisexual American history]]\n*[[Gay men in American history]]\n*[[History of bisexuality]]\n*[[History of lesbianism]]\n*[[Lesbian American history]]\n*[[LGBT history]]\n*[[:Category:LGBT history]]\n*[[Gay and Lesbian Pride Month]] (June)\n*[[Transgender American history]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://lgbthistorymonth.com/ LGBT History Month website \u2013 US]\n*[http://www.lgbthistorymonth.org.uk/ LGBT History Month website \u2013 UK]\n*[http://www.lgbthistorymonth.co.uk/ Schools OUT UK's Official Guide to LGBT History Month magazine and Diversity Dashboard]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20190508094843/http://www.lgbthistorymonthmagazine.co.uk/ LGBT History Month Magazine: The Official Guide to LGBT History Month UK]\n* https://www.minus18.org.au/index.php/get-involved/campaigns/history-month\n{{LGBT history}}\n\n[[Category:Recurring events established in 1994]]\n[[Category:LGBT history]]\n[[Category:LGBT events in the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT events in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:February observances]]\n[[Category:October observances]]\n[[Category:Commemorative months]]\n[[Category:Observances in the United States]]\n[[Category:Observances in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "DavidBrooks", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix markup", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LGBT_History_Month"}
